      "name": "Skinslough",
      "sections": [
        {
          "image": {
            "image": "Sidebar_1_AdviceAndRules.png",
            "name": "Advice and Rules",
            "type": "image"
          },
          "name": "The Wax Man",
          "sidebar_heading": "Advice and Rules",
          "sidebar_type": "advice_and_rules",
          "sources": [
            {
              "link": {
                "alt": "Pathfinder #207: Resurrection Flood pg. 88",
                "aonid": 249,
                "game-obj": "Sources",
                "name": "Pathfinder #207: Resurrection Flood pg. 88",
                "type": "link"
              },
              "name": "Pathfinder #207: Resurrection Flood",
              "page": 88,
              "type": "source"
            }
          ],
          "subtype": "sidebar",
          "text": "In the many taverns around the Inner Sea, there are tales of a creature called the Wax Man, a mysterious figure whose features are kept hidden by a deep, dark hood. If these stories are to be believed, beneath his voluminous robes, the Wax Man's skin shifts of its own volition. Whether the Wax Man is a skinslough, suffers from another condition, or is even real remains a subject of nervous debate.",
          "type": "section"
        }
      ],
      "sources": [
        {
          "link": {
            "alt": "Pathfinder #207: Resurrection Flood pg. 88",
            "aonid": 249,
            "game-obj": "Sources",
            "name": "Pathfinder #207: Resurrection Flood pg. 88",
            "type": "link"
          },
          "name": "Pathfinder #207: Resurrection Flood",
          "page": 88,
          "type": "source"
        }
      ],
      "text": "A skinslough looks like a humanoid whose skin moves like an ill-fitting coat, independent of the underlying muscle and connective tissue. Nightmarish to behold, their touch spreads their terrible disease to others. Skinsloughs are often mistaken for floodslain, a type of undead also brought about by water. Unlike floodslain, however, not all skinsloughs arise after drowning in a flood. Sailors cast overboard, lone explorers of remote lakes, and even people who tumble down abandoned wells can all become one of these foul creatures. Certainly, many skinsloughs arise from the Deluge, but their existence is far more widespread.  \n  \n Unlike most other intelligent undead, skinsloughs aren't exclusively cruel and merciless, though many are. They retain a flicker of memory from their past lives and often actively avoid contact with anyone. Skinsloughs who have experienced the screaming terror that's so often a reaction to their appearance, however, give in to anger and work to spread their pain to others.",
      "type": "section"
    }
  ],
  "sources": [
